unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C;

B = (0,0);
C = (32,0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc(B,10,0,180),arc(C,16,0,180));

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(A,foot(A,B,C),B,10));

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$h$", (A + foot(A,B,C))/2, W);
label("$32$", (B + C)/2, S);
[/asy]

Then $\tan B = \frac{h}{AB}$ and $\tan C = \frac{h}{AC},$ so $AB = \frac{2}{3} h$ and $AC = 2h.$  By the Pythagorean Theorem on triangle $ABC,$
\[h^2 + \left( \frac{2}{3} h \right)^2 = (2h)^2.\]Then $\frac{13}{9} h^2 = 4h^2,$ so $h = 0$ or $h = \frac{36}{\sqrt{23}}.$  Since $h$ is an altitude, $h > 0,$ so $h = \frac{36}{\sqrt{23}}.$

The area of triangle $ABC$ is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 32 \cdot \frac{36}{\sqrt{23}} = \boxed{\frac{576}{\sqrt{23}}}.$

